item.caption: HM COLONOSCOPY - Edited Result - FINAL (08/08/2016)

paragraph.content: Gastroenterology Encounter for screening for malignant neoplasm of colon
Dx Referred by James A Knight, MD
DATE OF BIRTH: AGE: PATIENT TYPE: RM #:
The patient is a 66-year-old gentleman who presents toKnight for a surveillance
colonoscopy. In 2008 adenomatous polyps were removed as well in 2003. His
most recent examination July 2011 did not demonstrate the presence of polyps.
There is no family history of colon polyps, colon cancer.
MONITORING: Oxygen saturation, blood pressure, heart rate monitored
MEDICATIONS FOR THE PROCEDURE: Include fentanyl 100 mcg, Versed 5 mg.
DESCRIPTION OF PROCEDURE: Informed consent was obtained. The patients past
medical history, medication list, and allergies were reviewed. Risks,
benefits, and alternatives have been discussed. Specific risks discussed
include those of bleeding, perforation, splenic injury, aspiration pneumonia,
side effects of sedative medication, possibility of missed lesions.
The patient was then placed in the left lateral decubitus position. IV
sedation was started in sequential fashion until the appropriate level of
consciousness was achieved. Digital rectal examination excluding the
prostate was within normal limits. Colonoscope was then advanced from the
anus to the cecum. The appendiceal orifice and ileocecal valve were
visualized. Cecum was photographed. Colonoscope was then slowly withdrawn.
Each colonic segment was evaluated carefully. Care was taken to inspect the
proximal aspects of the IC valve, haustral folds, as well as flexures.
Mucosal abnormalities were not visualized. Retroflexed view of the rectum
was unremarkable, and the photograph was obtained. Colonoscope was then
withdrawn from the patient. The procedure was terminated, well tolerated.
No immediate complications. Preparation was adequate.
According to current colon cancer screening guidelines, this patients next
colonoscopy should take place in 5 years.
A pre-sedation re-evaluation was performed immediately prior to beginning the procedure.
Medications: Procedural sedation with Fentanyl, Versed
ASA 2 - Patient with mild systemic disease with no functional limitations
Post Procedure plan: Return to same level of care
I assessed the patient and find that the patient is in satisfactory condition to proceed with the planned procedure and sedation plan.
I have explained the risk, benefits, and alternatives to the procedure. The patient understands and agrees to proceed. Yes
